## Example usage

    # Install: just drop the binary somewhere on PATH
    $ curl -LO https://.../my-gather-linux-amd64
    $ chmod +x my-gather-linux-amd64 && mv my-gather-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/my-gather

    # Simplest case: point at a pt-stalk output dir, get a report next to it
    $ my-gather /var/lib/pt-stalk/2026_04_15_140523

    Parsed 47 files (2 skipped, see report). Wrote report to:
      /var/lib/pt-stalk/2026_04_15_140523/report.html

    # Explicit output path
    $ my-gather /path/to/collection -o /tmp/case-12345.html

    # Time window within the collection
    $ my-gather /path/to/collection --from 14:05:30 --to 14:07:00

    # Quiet mode for scripts; exit 0 if report written, 2 if no usable data
    $ my-gather /path/to/collection -o out.html -q

    # Version and self-check
    $ my-gather --version
    my-gather 1.0.0 (commit abc1234, go1.23.4, built 2026-04-21)

## Errors (typed)

Package-level sentinel and typed errors in the `mygather` module:

- `ErrNotAPtStalkDir`       — path exists but has no recognizable pt-stalk files
- `ErrEmptyCollection`      — pt-stalk files present but all empty/truncated
- `ErrOutputPathExists`     — --output path exists and --force not given
- `ErrUnreadableInput`      — permission or IO problem on input
- `type ParseError struct { File string; Line int; Cause error }` —
  non-fatal per-file parse failures, collected and rendered in the report's
  "Missing/unparseable files" section rather than aborting.

Exit codes:
  0 — report written
  1 — usage error (bad flags)
  2 — no usable data in input
  3 — output could not be written
  4 — input unreadable

